caption:
A reminder that everything you see if not as it seems. So do have loose skin. Sometimes I get messages asking if I’ve had surgery or why don’t I share about it or if I can post a picture!!!

I haven’t had surgery as you can see plus when it’s time I will let y’all know. Yes one day I will get it removed.

Anyone who has lost a extreme amount of weight has loose skin. It’s part of it but it’s nothing to be ashamed of. It reminds me of how hard I have worked. 

What sucks I can’t see all the progress that I’m actually making. I retain water even with the Whole Foods and eliminating a lot of stuff but it’s not as bad. I am not eliminating my supplements till we are closer to the stage. The skin is heavy and it does cause back pain and it gets in the way. So form is hard with some exercises but I do the best I can.

Poses and good leggings help hide everything. Black definitely hides the skin very well. Sets like this help @gymshark @gymsharkwomen 

Don’t let skin stop you from starting because I will take it over being where I started.

Next DietBet starts 5/24 this is the game got me started and helped me stay accountable and love the shop we have. Link in the bio to sign up.

caption:
STRESS + TRAINING ⬇️

Now - I need to be honest with you guys, since launching my coaching in November it’s been INCREDIBLE. I’m so incredibly proud of me, Matt and our team (🥺). But now and then I lose track of day to day things, I sometimes find myself un-inspired by not giving myself time to fully relax. 

In the middle of trying to move house, organise our new office, employ new staff, work heavily on my socials (because I love it ofc). I’m feeling super duper stressed, which is inevitable right now. 

So what impact does this have on my training / what do I need to do?

👉🏼 decrease weight / try to avoid any added stressors 

👉🏼 potentially look at reducing volume / intensity 

👉🏼 ensure I’m not in a strict deficit / deficit at all (unnecessary added stress / depending on individual)

👉🏼 add in mindset work or yoga 

👉🏼 take some time OUT. 

Our daily life can take its toll sometimes and we all appreciate and understand that sometimes there is nothing you can do ✨

“Do you train only for aesthetics?” A question I was asked yesterday which got me thinking. 

Ask me the same question 4 years ago, abso-f*cking-lutley I trained for aesthetics and there is nothing wrong if you enjoy that. But I didn’t enjoy it. I had an eating disorder at the time and I was so obsessed with what I looked like it was damaging. 

Looking in the mirror and pinching my skin. Every inch of my body. I didn’t even care at the time that I was unhealthy due to an ED. I was just so self absorbed in a “body” bubble. 

Focusing solely on aesthetics was Damaging because that’s the ONLY thing I cared about. I didn’t care about my health, being underweight, being tired, being weak. I just wanted to look a certain way. And to be honest I didn’t even know what that was? 

When I started to focus on performance  and being physically the fittest I could be. Good sh*t happened. I was eating more, moving well and living a healthier life. And yeah guess what, physical results will follow naturally. And that for me is important to take away. The 3 elements; a mixture of focusing on performance & health and aesthetics will follow (not forced) is a happy medium for me 😃

Listen to your body & make sure to take those rest days as it’s alllll a part of your recovery👏🏼💜

This sunshineeee tho 🤗🌿☀️🍀 

With this month being mental health awareness month, I wanted to talk about mine for a sec ❣️

Personally, I have a type of high-functioning anxiety, which basically means I have a hard time slowing the f*ck down lmao. I have a really hard time relaxing and taking time to myself to do things that I enjoy, because I tend to feel guilty if I am not doing something like school work or work in general. 

Being in STEM as well, it can be really easy to let school take over and for you to not have a life. If I’m being honest, I am SO GUILTY of this. I have gotten better as the semesters have progressed, but I can’t tell you how many weekend nights I’ve spent doing homework instead of enjoying myself. All I know is that the ones doing homework outweigh the other ☠️

I have a family history of anxiety and depression, and don’t get me wrong I’ve definelty had my rough points. However right now, I can honestly say that I am surrounded by people who love me and support me and that helps immensely ❤️

I hope that this relates to some of you, and take it as a sign to know that IT IS OKAY TO RELAX - because don’t worry I have to remind myself every day... or quite literally have my boyfriend take my computer away from me ☠️

But anyway.. the WERKOUTTT:

🌳 barbell shoulder press 4x6: focus on going heavy and keep that core ENGAGED! You want to focus on moving your head around the bar instead of the bar around your head.

Hello everyone! I thought I'd do a little intro and even though most of y'all know a little about me already I'd like to tell you morrrre.My husband, Mark and I own 2 personal training gyms...one in Troy, MI and now we're expanding to Land O Lakes, FL near Tampa. 

I am a 41 yeats young mama of 3. Fitness has been a part of my life since 2000. I was introduced to weights and the gym by husband. I had always been a skinny weak unathletic self conscious teenager and lifting weights brought out my inner bad as beast. I was leaving my gym sessions feeling like I had never felt in my life. The more I lifted, the stronger and more confident I became in more ways than one. Weight lifting changed my life, my mood, my self concept, my outlook on life and as an added bonus gave my skinny scrawny body shape. I am forever grateful for this lifestyle and am excited to lead more women into it at our new studio in Florida beginning June 2021. Looking forward to helping change lives and improving the Flordian Bikini Mama Bods! 👙

The Reverse Band Method - The bench press you see here, has an "ascending strength curve". What does that mean? As you get closer to completing the lift, the tension of the bar required to hit the lockout position decreases 📉

By using "The Reverse Band Method". The lifter/athlete is able to manipulate "The Strength Curve" by handling supra-maximally loads at higher volumes 💪🏼 

The goal is to explode into the bar and accelerate as fast as possible through the entire range of motion 🧨

Always remember that any method is just another tool in your toolbox 🛠🧰

Benefits 👇🏼
🔘 Greater HTMU recruitment
🔘 Neuromuscular Efficiency
🔘 Motor Patterns
🔘 Hypertrophy
🔘 Getting Absolutely Jacked

guys. this outdoor workout was EVERYTHING. it was the sweatiest I’ve been in a while during a workout & I LOVED IT. something about this full body lift while soaking up some vitamin D just hit different 🥵

ONLY KETTLEBELLS & YOUR BODY needed for today’s workout. grab a kettlebell (or dumbbell works too) & get to work 👏🏽

the workout ⬇️
superset #1: 3 sets 
🌻12 KB swings 
🌻10 each snatch
superset #2: 3 sets 
🌻8 each racked lunges (heavy in down arm medium in racked arm) 
🌻10 close grip push ups (I’ve been working SO HARD to get better at these & it’s paying off) 
superset #3: 3 sets 
🌻10 goblet squat to press 
🌻16 plank pull throughs
finisher: 3 rounds 
🌻12 squat jumps, 2 shoulder taps to hop ins, & 12 reverse crunches 

get that booty outside today & get a sweat in (and then rest when you are done 👏🏽)

Long post :// Appreciation Post:// 
-
-
I have been with Dylan for 8 months, a year in October. 
It was a shot in the dark when I applied for his coaching because after my last competition, I just felt lost and didn’t have the drive for fitness anymore. 
Dylan took me on and helped me fall in love with not only my love for fitness again, but my career. 
-
Let me say that, he hands down amazes me not only as a coach, but as person. 
He strives for greatness, not only for himself, but he wants the same for his clients. 
It puts his all into his coaching. 
You can tell because he is there for 24:7 support. 
-
He’s not just a coach, he’s a friend. 
I’ve had days where I’m not motivated and just have wanted to give up but Dylan pushes you for success. 
Not many coaches will understand that your mental health is your top priority. 
He not only tires to understand and help, but for his female clients.. he tries to understand our “monthly visitor” so he can help his best way without us feeling as crappy as we do. 
He tries to understand the Why and the root of the problem so you can continue to thrive. 
If you know me, you know mental health and the understanding of it is a huge thing for me. 
-
Something I don’t talk about because it’s very personal, but I like to be open with my following because it is part of my journey, is that not only do I have anxiety to the point I can’t make it to the gym most days, but I have an Eating Disorder and I have been slowly recovering. 
-
Dylan has been a major help with getting me back to loving food and making food my friend again.
He’s helped me to eat nutritious food that fuels my body for success without feeling guilty or the need to go do hours of cardio to burn it off. 
Not only do I feel better physically and stronger, but mentally. 
Thank you to the real one 🤟🏻

Take a time out ✨

Sometimes you just need to drop everyone and have fun with friends or family. 
Pushing yourself and working hard is great but when it starts to become a chore it’s time to have a rest. 
THE GYM INCLUDED
Fitness is something you’re supposed to enjoy no matter what the reason for doing it. If you are feeling awful before during and after and dread the idea of going, just have a break. Remember why you started and remember why you fell in love with what you’re doing in the first place.
Put yourself, mentally and physically first: the rest can wait 

Also happy Friday!! It’s finally the weekend 🥰

The machine shoulder press is a variation of the seated barbell shoulder press used to strengthen the muscles of the shoulders.

One would use the machine shoulder press as a way to perform the pressing movement pattern with a focus on isolating the shoulders. One can better isolate certain muscle groups with a machine due to its fixed movement pattern.

The machine shoulder press is best added towards the end of your shoulder workout if you are training for hypertrophy, after you’ve used other more compound variations to work your push muscles.

Helloooo everyone! I’m so happy it’s Friday, this week has really dragged at least for me ¯\_(ツ)_/¯ Remember what I said yesterday about getting in and out of the gym quick?! I decided to do my push day as an EMOM yesterday and it was AMAZING!! In and out in 40 minutes 👏🤗

An EMOM stands for Every Minute on the Minute. Once you perform the exercise (either for reps or for time), the time in the minute you have left over is your rest. Once the next minute starts, you start the next exercise! ⏱ These are a super effective way to get in a good workout when you’re crunched for time or just a great way to keep your heart rate up while you work out. These can be modified for any body part, or just for a quick HIIT day. Let me know what you think!

Workout
⏱Burpees x 10
⏱Chest press x 12
⏱Upright row to lat raise x 8 each
⏱Shoulder press x 12
⏱Tricep extension x 12
⏱Rear delt fly x 12

I did this 5x through and it only took 30 minutes

What I wish I knew when I started training! 

I started training around 3 years ago. Before then I was a dancer with amazing cardio but very little strength. 
Since then I’ve worked my arse off and absolutely loved the journey!

What I wish I knew back then: 
1️⃣ Food is fuel and not the enemy! 
2️⃣ Macros! Know the difference and importance of protein, carb and fats!
3️⃣ Progressive Overload- you need to get the heavy weights up and really push yourself! You won’t grow if you use the same weight forever. 
4️⃣ Recovery is incredibly important and crucial for building muscle.
5️⃣ Try new things! Don’t be scared to go into the free weight section or to try new equipment.

I’ve truly been finding my way in my training lately and couldn’t be happier/more excited.
Another 6 mile run awaits me today and so keeping my body fresh and as loose as possible is absolutely essential.
For me working out is truly my passion, true finding in life!  Without it, I am very lost.  Whether it’s through boxing,  roadwork (running), or lifting weights.. I truly apply myself fully to these things and it’s never to impress anybody else but because I truly enjoy it!
It’s one of the few passions that I never have to rely on others for. 
I love it so much that sometimes I wonder what my life would have been if I pursued my boxing/fitness aspirations full-time.. but it’s too late now.  For the time being I will always give my best in the elements I can control, my intensity and desire to be better.  I do things because you aren’t.

Orange Socks Gains 🍊 

Loading the eccentric part of the movement until i feel like my knees and ankles are going to give way. 😂

Most people always focus on the drive up on most exercises and forget to actually control the weight. On the way down is just as important as the way up!

A rep range of 6-12 and this was set 4 for 6 at 400kg. We build from here. People think 10 is a magic number but the truth is there is not a set number of reps you need to do to grow. Time under tension...

🌈 Foods That Are Killing Your Sex Drive
-
🥤Soda. A study published in the Central European Journal of Urology linked it to bad news below the belt as well: Researchers found that high fructose corn syrup combined with refined sugars increased the risk of erectile dysfunction by raising cholesterol levels and causing vascular damage.
-
🍭Artificial Sweeteners. Sacrifice sugar for controversial aspartame, and you're at risk for lowered levels of serotonin and dopamine—the chemicals that control libido and keep you happy.
-
🥫Canned Goods. Many aluminum cans are lined with BPA, a chemical that can cause a whole host of sexual health issues.
-
🍢Licorice. Studies found that liquorice contains the compound that reduces testosterone levels in men.
-
🍺Alcohol. A beer belly is just the beginning. A 2014 study published in the Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine linked excess alcohol consumption to several areas of sexual dysfunction, including "profound testosterone suppression." One more reason to drink responsibly.
-
🥪Deli Meat. Fatty meats can absorb PVC, causing some undesirable hormonal changes.
-
🥦Marijuana. It can detract from one’s sexual drive (and ability) by lowering testosterone levels for up to 24 hours, according to a study from NCB
-
🥗Mint. The menthol in mint can lower testosterone, depleting your sex drive. Turn to one of these halitosis-fighting foods instead.

HOW’D I DO IT? 🙈🙈🙈

You really don’t know how much you’ve grown until you do side by side progress pictures… holy crap 🤒

So… what’d I change?
1. FOOD. I started eating way more (still 80/20 clean of course) and started listening to body, and actually ATE WHEN I WAS HUNGRY and stopped tracking my food because the numbers freaked me out. 
2. COMPOUND MOVEMENTS. I used to do like every exercise I saw on Instagram and never really understood that the only way to grow is to go heavy with compound exercises which brings me to my next point…
3. PROGRESSIVE OVERLOAD. it’s almost impossible to grow if you aren’t increasing in your weight!!!!! You should at least be trying to add 2.5 lbs each week if anything. Any weight counts!!
4. I STOPPED EGO LIFTING. ego lifting really took a toll on my body and once I put aside the ego and went down in weight and focused on form I saw HUGE changes!!

The last 8 months I’ve grown so much physically and mentally and am overall just so proud of how far I’ve come! I definitely recommend taking progress pictures every now and then so you can see how much you’ve grown!!!

I always thought I'd be happier being smaller 

Truth is, I was miserable in the picture on the left. This was just before Christmas. I was going through some personal things and my appetite disappeared. I actually thought to myself... 

'no appetite means I'll lose weight, I'll be slim and I'll finally be happy with my body' 

🤦‍♀️❌ 

This wasn't the case. I was far from happy. 

The picture on the right is me now and I'm finally happy. 

I'm finally happy because training is amazing and I have a healtheir relationship with food. I'm enjoying life and not constantly worrying about what I see in the mirror. 

And it feels so damn good. 

There will come a time when I feel like I'm in the head space to lean out again. That might be in 2 weeks. That might be in 2 months. That might be in 2 years. 

But for now I'm happy.

I can’t even explain how happy i am because since i’ve been in a deficit i wasn’t able to go super heavy and i couldn’t really push myself into any prs. It’s a real struggle when you want to loose body fat but also want to build muscles and strength🙈😂 So here i am out of my deficit and just eating something around my maintenance. I’m just gonna finish up some of my workouts with cardio but mostly i want to be focused on gaining muscles. 
Do i still have body fat? Clearly yes. My stomach is probably one of my biggest insecurities. But i’d like to look at the longer terms. More muscles you have more calories your body burns at the rest. That’s why i feel like my next cut will be more successful. And as soon as you understand how to loose weight it seems so easy🥰

Day 5 of getting up at 5am for the gym!! 

I’ve been going to the gym at 6am and it has felt goooood. I love going early because those post-workout endorphins really set me up for a good day. Buuut let’s not pretend getting up early is easy. 

Here are some tips!

1. GO. TO. BED. EARLY. If you get a full nights rest it’ll be so much easier to get up. You can’t expect to feel good if you get up 2hrs earlier without going to bed 2hrs earlier. 

2. Set out your outfit, pack your bag and have an easy breakfast ready to go the night before. Less time in the morning thinking/making decisions means you can sleep a bit more and you’re less likely to forget things (I forgot my mask twice this week because I didn’t prepare properly 🥲) 

Some easy breakfast that I like are: overnight oats, toast & PB + banana, or if you’re really fancy, you can make egg cups in a muffin tin!

3. It will get easier! The first day is always the hardest, but if you keep up a good sleep schedule your body will get used to it!

Hi everyone...it’s been a while😊I’m sure that you’re all aware, it’s mental health awareness week so I thought that I’d share something with you that I’ve been really struggling with the past few months so that others know that they’re not alone!

For the past 3 years I’ve been battling an eating disorder and I told myself that 2021 would be the year that I (somewhat) beat it. Since January I’ve been on my recovery journey and I’ve managed to put on a stone which is a very big deal for me. 

It’s hard to not think about it in a negative way because that’s what my disorder wants me to do but I’ve managed to now train my brain into remembering that the weight I’ve gained is a positive and not a negative. That mindset shift definitely didn’t happen overnight and it’s something that I have to work on every single day but I’m proud of how far I’ve come so far even if I do slip up some days. 

It’s been hard coming out of lockdown being bigger than when I went into it but I have to keep reminding myself that it’s my body and mind getting better! 

I just want everyone who goes through this to know that they’re not alone and that we’re all in it together. We shouldn’t see food as an enemy as FOOD IS FUEL and we need it to survive❤️

When your dieting you’ll inevitably get to a stage where your weight will stay the same or you won’t be losing as much as you’d want...

This is completely normal and should be expected!

But what do you do when this happens?

First of all wait a week or 2 before making any drastic changes, your weight and body fat might keep dropping, as we all know weight can fluctuate a fair bit from day to day

If 1 or 2 weeks go by and there’s no change to weight or noticeable body change, you have 2 options to keep the progress moving

1️⃣ Increase energy output 

Basically burn more calories in the day, this can be done by upping your step count, adding cardio in, increasing cardio and generally just being more active in the day

2️⃣ Decrease energy input

By this I mean lower your calorie consumption, if you are tracking calories then lower your daily calories by 100-200, nothing crazy but enough to get the scales moving again

If your not tracking calories then you can do this by lowing portion sizes, less snacking, eating less calorific foods which are high in volume to keep you full, and upping protein intake

But generally just eating less!!

Adapting is apart of dieting! 

Let’s go 💪🟠

Rien ne vaut un mental d’acier.  Personne ne fera les efforts à ta place. Lève toi chaque jour avec l’envie de tout casser, l’envie de réussir, l’envie de te dépasser. 

Toi aussi, trouve ta routine... et deviens un champion. Pas pour les autres. Rien que pour toi et personne d’autre. 💪🏽
Le regard des gens n’est pas important. Au fond, ce qui compte, c’est ce que tu décides de faire de ce que la nature t’a donné. 
Crois en toi.

⚠️ ATTENTION ⚠️ 
Toutes les personnes ayant eu recours à la SLEEVE vous diront que c’était l’opération de la dernière chance.. Et ce fut aussi le cas pour moi !

Certes cette opération bariatrique, non sans risque, est une réelle baguette magique qui vous permettra de perdre de nombreux kilos en début de parcours ! 

MAIS sans un rééquilibrage alimentaire et une pratique sportive cela ne pourra pas fonctionner sur le long terme ! Nombreux et nombreuses sont ceux qui reprennent du poids après 1 ou 2 ans..

Nous perdons très vite du poids au début !  Et ce, même en mangeant des aliments gras ou sucrés mais cela ne dur pas. C’est ici qu’il faut être vigilant car rapidement les bienfaits de l’opération s’estompent et nous revoilà face à nos démons ! 

Il est donc primordial de prendre conscience, qu’il ne s’agira pas simplement de se faire opérer ! Mais d’adopter un nouveau style de vie : une alimentation saine et une pratique sportive adéquate ! Cela demandera beaucoup de sacrifices, d’efforts et une réelle prise de conscience ! Il faut être prêt à changer de vie 💪🏻

🩺 N’hésitez pas à faire appel à un nutritionniste ou un diététicien pour vous épauler ! 

Pour la pratique sportive, faites ce qui vous plait ! Vous anime ! 
Du fitness, de la natation, de la course, de la danse, du cyclisme, peut importe du moment que cela vous rend heureux ! 

Ou comme moi, lancez-vous un nouveau défi ! La MUSCULATION ! 
Apprenez ! 
Trompez-vous ! 
Amusez-vous ! 
Prenez y du plaisir ! 
Entourez-vous de personnes qui vous soutiendront ! 

Mais en tout cas, ne lâchez rien 💪🏻💪🏻 !!! 

A toutes celles ou ceux qui partagent mon expérience ou qui auraient des questions n’hésitez pas à me contacter en MP ! 
Je me ferais un réel plaisir de vous répondre !

When it comes to lifting heavy, I’m a big believer in creating your OWN weightlifting belt. Not an actual belt, I’m talking INTRA-ABDOMINAL PRESSURE. 

However, a belt definitely enhances your ability to stabilize the spine, so long as you maintain constant tension in the abdominal cavity! 💪

Then why use a belt? 🤔 
For starters, a belt is the perfect tool to reinforce the muscles of the trunk. Secondly, it protects the low back...spine safety is always the top priority, ESPECIALLY when testing your maximal strength..By no means will I sacrifice my health to tell people I lifted “X” amount of weight but walk with a limp for months on end.

How do we use one PROPERLY? 🏋️‍♀️ 
As stated above, we must learn to breathe and brace before we even think about starting our lifts. A big breath through the mouth (Belly breath) will expand the diaphragm downward, thus, creating pressure within our intra-abdominal cavity. 

Researchers have shown that athletes who wear a belt correctly tend to lift heavier weights with more explosive power. They are also able to maintain their trunk stiffness for more reps during higher rep maximum lifts like an 8 RM attempt 🔥 

Warning ⚠️ 
Repetitive use of a belt will cause the body to rely on the support of the belt. Which will begin  weaken the core it uses the belt as a crutch more than a tool to increase performance. 

S/O @koachkyle & @coach_miguel10 for the morale support 😂

Why are some people reaching their goals, and some people not?

-

Everyone that goes to the gym has a goal in one way or another, whether that’s losing weight, getting stronger, getting fitter etc, but realistically how many people are actually arsed about achieving that goal? I genuinely mean it, I see so many people go in and just doss about on phones or just stand chatting constantly expecting the weight to just fall off, or the body to just grow. So much so that sometimes when you see someone attempt a huge lift, work to true failure, or even just be absolutely soaked after a session, they almost seem like the odd ones out.

-

For me personally, I know that each time I go in, I know exactly what numbers I need to hit, and I give 100% in order to do that, and to be honest, the results don’t lie. My strength has increased massively, my body has changed massively, and my overall mindset has also changed massively over the course of this last training block. I genuinely have stopped caring what people think when I’m in there now, if I want to film something to get feedback? Sound I’ll do that. If I want to shout at myself to get a bit more hyped for my topsets? Sound I’ll do that. 

-

This isn’t meant to come across by any means as an arrogant post, but more of a demonstration and example of what you can achieve when you fully put both your mind and effort to something. I am pretty new to bodybuilding since making the switch, but I will hit my goals regardless, and if that means being humbled by being told to knock the weight down/ improve form, or have to ask others who are more experienced for advice, then I’m going to do that.

-

At the end of the day, the one thing I love about training, is you get out of it exactly what you put in. All the effort you put in is reflected in the outcome of your training as a whole. So therefore, if you’re only putting in 30%, don’t expect 100% back.

JAMMIE DODGER OATS 🍓🍪

Think I’ve finally smashed this baked oats trend I can’t lie. At first I was kinda questioning the hype but this one might be my favourite one that I’ve made so far it was so so good. Honestly if your gonna try and make one, make this one 🥰🤩

RECIPE: 
- 60g oats 
- 100ml oat milk 
- 10g egg whites 
- 30g @myprotein vanilla protein 
- 50g raspberries 
- 1 jammie dodger 
- Half a banana 
- 10g white chocolate 

1. Preheat the oven to 200°C
2. Mix together all of the ingredients apart from the raspberries, white chocolate and Jammie dodger cookie
3. Top the mixture with the raspberries and the jammie dodger 
4. Bake for 20 mins 
5. While that cooks melt the white chocolate and drizzle over the oats once they’ve finished cooking 

Let me know if you make this and what you think of it! 😋

A quote I was OBSESSED with in high school. A quote that made it into my quote book recently 🤣

Is it someone in your life? 
Is it something someone said to you?
Is it lack of access to a gym? 
Is it a job?
Is it your own self and beliefs?

Get rid of anything that holds you back from achieving what you want. You don’t need that shit in your life. You want to chase your goals? You want to go after what you want? Do it. And whatever is it weighing you down, is definitely something you don’t need.

caption:
Quick hour back session blasted out after work. A lot of focus on Lats here 💪🏼 

*Lats - Latissimus Dorsi*

Exercise 1 - Single lat pulldown. Sit with the back straight and feel the stretch. Tuck your elbow into your side at the bottom and squeeze the lat. start light and work up. 1 set of 15 reps of light weight. 1 set of 12 reps moderate weight. 1 set of 10 reps heavy. 

Exercise 2 - Bent over rows. Excuse my fat hole in the video. Bend the knees with feet shoulder width apart and keep the back straight. Maintain good posture, lift as if strings are behind you pulling your elbows back. (If lifting heavy remember to wear a belt). Bar - 1x15reps. 40kg - 1x12-15reps. 60kg - 1x10-12reps. 

Exercise 3 - Rotary lat pull. This gives the back an amazing stretch. Keep tempo slow and controlled and tuck elbows into your hips at the bottom of the lift and squeeze the lats. 3 sets of a weight your comfortable with. If able to up it, even better. 

Exercise 4 - Lat pulldown. Keep slow and controlled. Don’t sit directly straight, arch the back a little and pull the bar into your chest. This gives your back a better squeeze, when going back up, really feel the stretch. 1 set of 15 - light to moderate weight. 1 set of 12 moderate to heavy weight. 1 set of 10 heavy weight. 

Exercise 5 - To finish. Single arm bent over rows. Find a bench and lift the weight. Keep elbow at around 90° and tuck into your hip at the peak. Don’t try to pull the dumbbells past your hip/back as this is over-extension and will cause back pain and injury. I used the same 20kg dumbbell for all 3 sets but if you’re able to go heavier in your 2/3rd set, do!

Also remember, using a weight your comfortable with is good but the real progress is upping the weight. You probably won’t get the same amount of reps/sets with the heavier weight to start with but over time you’ll get stronger and be more able to lift more. This is called progressive overload. As long as your form stays good, it will come. Enjoy 👍🏼

🤷🏼‍♀️CAN I GROW MUSCLE WHILST IN A DEFICIT?
⠀
Simple answer? Yes
⠀
⚠️When in a calorie deficit, many people focus on losing fat mass & instantly think they have to eat less of everything.
⠀
🙅🏼‍♀️Whilst you are aiming to lower calorie intake, eating less of each macro won’t be beneficial. As a result, you will lose that water weight & the fat mass, but your muscles will start to atrophy due to diminished protein. This happens because the muscle protein breakdown now outweighs the synthesis.
⠀
🤷🏼‍♀️How do I stop this?
When in a deficit, because your carb intake needs are so high, most subtraction will be from that (not too much though, gotta be even!).
⠀
🧮For example, you’re in 250kcal deficit & you’re 70kg- at 3g per 70kg, that’s 210g of carbs= 788kcal & that’s only the minimal according to ACSM guidelines for athletes on a ‘lower’ training day.
At a higher day you’ll be consuming 5-7g (350-490g)- that’s a lot of carbs! For this reason, we have calories to deduct mainly from the carbs (You also get energy from fats & these can be played around with)
⠀
🆙Because of the lower calories, we up the protein amount. Recommendations vary, but in general you should be on 1.1-1.2g per kg a day.
📈I recommend upping this to 1.3-1.5 when entering deficit; this ensures that MPS outweighs MPB & your muscles will continue to grow & form new proteins.
⠀
💪🏼Furthermore- focus on heavy resistance training, to stimulate the microtears in muscles to repair & grow. Also incorporating HIIT & cardio, promoting fat burning (cannot target), will aid in your fat loss goal.
⠀
End message: be in a calorie deficit (not too big), aim for high protein consumption & strength train 💪🏼

WHO ARE YOU DOING IT FOR?

When I first started my fitness journey, I wanted to look good for other people and how they see me. This is a toxic mindset, and you shouldn’t be doing things to impress other people. 

Now, I lift weights for ME, and how it makes me feel. I feel amazing when I lift, physically and mentally. Lifting is like an escape for me. 

Lifting is SO much more than just aesthetics. For a lot of people it’s a distraction from the hard reality of their lives. 

So my question to you is who are you doing it for? If you don’t answer yourself, step back and ask yourself if you’re doing this for the right reasons. YOU DO STUFF FOR YOU. You are your own biggest supporter in life 💕

Happy Friday everyone!!! I hope you all have a great weekend & stay safe🥰

Got up at 5:30 AM today for myself & myself only 💪
-
Yesterday was a bit of an off day, so I committed myself to starting off today with a killer leg day. Since it was so early, there was barely anyone else at the gym. Nevertheless, I really pushed myself. Usually when working out, I find it helpful to feed off other’s energy. I can get in a good work out by myself but when there’s someone else going hard, I can complete a REALLY good workout. So, it was a really interesting mind challenge to work out so early when no one was making me do so. Overall, I did enjoy it & while I’m not sure if I’ll make it a habit yet, it was a really solid experience.

Butterfly 🦋 im Stehen ist eine sehr effektive Brustübung, die ihr nahezu überall machen könnt. Ihr braucht lediglich ein Widerstandsband und eine Möglichkeit dies zu befestigen, wie z. B. ein Treppengeländer.

So gehts: Greift das Band an beiden Enden und haltet es auf Brusthöhe. Eure leicht gebeugten Arme zeigen im 180-Grad-Winkel nach außen. Jetzt beide Arme zusammenführen, bis sich eure Hände in der Mitte treffen. Haltet die Spannung einen kurzen Moment und kehrt anschließend kontrolliert in die Ausgangsposition zurück 💪

➡️ 3 Sätze je 10-15 Wiederholungen pro Satz

🔥Trainiert großen Brustmuskel. 

Trainiert ihr gern mit Widerstandsbändern? 🔥

You know what that means? Another Hawai'i related topic! Mahalo nui (thank you very much) to everyone who responded to my story question on Hawai'i topics <3 
.
Today I'm telling you why I'm proud to be Native Hawaiian, which I'm 100% proud to be. NOTE: Being Native Hawaiian is an ethnicity and not everyone who lives in/grew up in Hawai'i is Hawaiian.
.
I'm proud for SO many reasons, but I'm primarily proud to be Hawaiian because of what this culture & it's people represent currently and have represented in the past. Hawaiians aren't perfect, and we can not all be put in the same box - but one thing I think we all are is resilient.
.
If you look at the history of Hawaiians - our form of dance & storytelling (hula) was banned (in 1830 considered a Pagan ritual), Hawaiian Kingdom was overthrown (1893) and Hawaiian language was banned (1896.) It wasn't until the 1980s (forty-ish years ago) that Hawaiian Language was formally taught again. We were considered “savages” too. Today we are even at higher risk for smoking, alcoholism, and obesity with less access to healthcare. I’m lucky to be part of the 7.4% of Hawaiians with a professional education & degree. 
.
AND YET WE STILL HAVE OUR PEOPLE, TRADITIONS, CULTURE, AND LANGUAGE EXISTING TODAY. We, as a people, are still fighting for our land, sovereignty and so much more, but the fact that we still exist and I am here today as a healthy educated kanaka screams resilient to me. 
.

A simple yet effective circuit to try at home or outdoors💥 

One thing I am grateful for in lockdown is how much it’s helped me to realise the gym is not the only place you can build lean muscle and maintain your body strength! 💪🏼

Home workouts for me have been just as effective as the gym, yes I cannot lift as heavy as I’d like too and am restricted in the machines I can use. However, after nearly a year away from the gym and going back yesterday, I still feel as strong and able to lift weights as I was before lockdown. 

Just wanted to share that with some of you who have reached out, wanting to loose weight and tone up, but don’t feel comfortable inside a gym or maybe don’t want to invest the money in memberships. 

A workout like the one above takes 20-30 mins to complete, don’t let yourself believe you don’t have the time. If you want it you’ll get it👏🏻

My 3 stone transformation...

I’ve been pretty quiet on social for a long long time. 

Like most people, lockdown 1 hit me pretty hard and I had really stopped taking care of myself mentally and physically. 

In August last year I decided to make a change and started dieting down from 101kg / nearly 16 stone.

Since then I’ve lost over 3 stone which is around 50 pounds or 23kg. 

The gym has always been a huge part of my life and has taught me a lot about self-discipline and mindset that carries over to other parts of life.

It took a worldwide pandemic to make me realise that life is pretty short, so if you’re going to follow your passion, do it. 

I’m now on my way to becoming a fully qualified personal trainer, have already started my online coaching business (@coachedbypickup) and have taken on clients who have dropped incredible amounts of weight. (Proof coming soon)

My own transformation was to prove to myself more than anything that I could do it. 

I’ve learned so much about nutrition and weight loss through hours of studying and through my own coach @jaymagee_wnbf_pro who has helped me get to this incredible transformation. 

It wasn’t easy but it was never supposed to be and I wouldn’t change a thing. 

(Tomorrow I’m heading to Nottingham for a full photoshoot so expect plenty more shots)

April was crazy. My last post on here was after I got through covid. My boyfriend and I thought he was all good since he got tested and was negative. Well, a few days after I was all good he started feeling symptoms. So I stayed home and took care of him. Then finals week came and I was super busy with all the final projects and exams. The semester was over, but then my boyfriend had a few days left here in Illinois before he moved states for an internship this summer. So of course I spent every moment I could with him. With all of that going on I ended only going to the gym 1 or 2 times. I counted the days I went to work and got over 10,000 steps in as a workout. I know I won’t achieve the 300 days of workouts this year, but I will still work my booty off because I’m proud of how far I’ve come and working out makes me feel so good. I went to the gym yesterday and I have lost some muscle, but not as much as I thought so at least there’s that. 
.
This summer I want to incorporate some habits into my life. 
🌼Get outside everyday
- Being outside makes me so happy and automatically puts me in a better mood.
🌼10,000+ steps
- I have a bad habit of going to the gym and then going home and not staying active the rest of the day. So getting in 10,000+ steps will help me stay active and moving throughout the day.
🌼Drink 90 oz water
- I know I don’t drink enough water like most, especially on days I work.
🌼Read
- I plan to read at least 5 books this summer. 

.
Here’s to summer, creating new habits, and being proud of myself.

¿Cómo podemos aumentar masa muscular? 

Para muchas personas aumentar masa muscular les parece más difícil que poder bajar sus porcentajes de grasa. Esto se debe porque para rebajar solamente tienes que consumir menos calorías de las que tú cuerpo necesita. 

Cuando hablamos de aumentar masa muscular. Debes de tener en cuenta que debes de consumir los alimentos que tus músculos necesitan antes y después de un buen entrenamiento de fuerzas. También, debes de consumir más calorías de la que tú cuerpo necesita para poder sobrevivir y esto algunas veces hace que las personas empiecen a consumir calorías y por este hecho aumentan su porcentaje de grasas en vez de masa muscular. 

Aquí les dejo algunos tips de cómo podemos incrementar nuestra masa muscular: 

- Cuando estés realizando ejercicios. Debes de enfocarte en el músculo en el cual estás trabajando y siempre tratar de hacer los ejercicios lentamente para que sientas el músculos. 
- No parar el ejercicio cuando sientas dolor en los músculos. Los expertos recomiendan siempre hacer ejercicio con el peso adecuado. Cuando sientas ese ardor o dolor en el músculo. Esto quiere decir que estás maltratando o rompiendo las fibras blancas del músculo y esto llevará a la hipertrofia durante el periodo de recuperación. 
- Realizar ejercicios de fuerzas de 3 a 5 veces por semana el mismo grupo muscular se trabaje de 1 a 2 veces, ya que el descanso muscular es fundamental para la hipertrofia.
- Ingerir alimentos ricos en proteínas. Para ganar masa muscular, es importante que la persona tenga una alimentación saludable y rica en proteínas, ya que son responsables de la manutención de las fibras musculares y, por consecuencia, están directamente relacionadas con la hipertrofia. Además de aumentar el consumo de proteínas, es importante también consumir carbohidratos, está es la mejor fuente de energía posible. 

COMETER LOS HIERROS Y CON BUENA ALIMENTACIÓN LOGRARÁS EL CUERPO QUE DESEAS. 

SE PACIENTE Y CONSISTENTE. ES UN PROCESO LARGO PERO SEGURO. 😍👏🏼♥️

🟦COMPOUND LIFTS🟧
.
⬛️A lot of people forget that a “Compound” exercise is just more than one muscle group working during the set. 
.
🟦Because these lifts use more muscles, they naturally take more energy... so it’s worthwhile starting with the big stuff and then moving to your smaller isolations.. 
.
🟧Don’t get caught up with doing lots of smaller exercises when you can get a lot of doing these bigger ones.. because realistically a 3x10-12 bicep curl isn’t going to help you get stronger. 
.

HOW TO GROW YOUR GLUTES ON A DIET🍑

Summer is coming and we all want that peachy booty right?😉

Here’s my top tips to grow the glutes whilst dieting⬇️

🍑 WORKOUTS: Ensure you are overloading your glutes by working out 2-3 times a week, targeting the lower body with 1 Glute day. Use booty bands to warm up and cool down allowing the muscles to engage throughout the workout. 

🍑 FUEL UP: Feed that booty of yours; know your protein consumption and hit it everyday. Protein such as meat, fish, quorn, whey isolate will be the best source. It will help the muscles mend and repair which allows them to growww✌🏼 

🍑 REST: Remember to leave 24-48 hours between lower body days to allow sufficient time to rest. If we over do it it can cause results to slow down. Resting is the time for growth remember.

🍑 PO: Progressive overload must be applied each week to ensure muscular growth is happening. Try adding weight, more reps, sets. There’s so many ways to apply progressive overload it doesn’t have to be loading up the weight each week. 

Hope these tips help you and let’s get peachy for summer🍑

BOXING PADWORK
The first few videos are quick highlights for people in a hurry, the last 6 are longer and more in depth of what was going on.

Smashed out a few rounds of padwork and on the bodypad. The padwork was to get back into the swing of things since it has been so long since doing any padwork but then we moved onto the simulation sparring using the bodypad as the countering target.

I realised afterwards that i need to incorporate more hooks into my counter punching as they’re probably my best punches but happy with my movement at the minute. Will keep doing this and get faster and more complex.

We took turns doing 3/4 minutes each on the pads for 3/4 rounds, and its safe to say that was enough. 

The hands down style feels so comfortable for me as i can see and read punches coming so well without my hands up but its very risky so I’ll be practicing guard up a lot.

𝐅𝐋𝐄𝐗 𝐅𝐑𝐈𝐃𝐀𝐘⁣
⁣
The final full week of training before we head off for a 10 day break!⁣
⁣
And it’s been a bit of a mixed bag⁣
⁣
One of the things I still find difficult is switching off⁣
⁣
I’m so involved & engaged in what I do every day⁣
⁣
That I find it tough to take a step back⁣
⁣
I know how beneficial it is⁣
⁣
And I also know how good I will feel having taken that break⁣
⁣
But it still creates a little apprehension⁣
⁣
10 days without training⁣
10 days away from ‘my things’⁣
10 days without the routine I love so much⁣
⁣
Of course, I can mitigate some of this⁣
⁣
But not all⁣
⁣
So, a little ‘stress’ building over the week that led to my appetite & digestion not being the best⁣
⁣
@adzfitness & I had always planned for this to be a chance to deload⁣
⁣
To allow all of the accumulated fatigue to dissipate⁣
⁣
And for me to come back feeling really fresh, ready for gyms to then open up again early June⁣
⁣
And let’s not forget that this is @lara.h0ward & I’s minimoon…we haven’t left the flat for 9 months!⁣
⁣
We will also likely have a little mini-cut, too⁣
⁣
To just trim back some of the bodyfat, restore some insulin sensitivity & let the appetite build again, too⁣
⁣
When you are pushing food, appetite can become the biggest issue⁣
⁣
Sensible use of time off, short periods of fat loss & other methods are so important to allow continued progress!⁣
⁣
⁣

One meal isn’t going to throw you off track but feeling guilty and adopting the fuck it attitude will.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
When you’re tracking your food, eating healthily and seeing results, it can be frustrating if you feel like you’ve “messed up.”⁠⁠
⁠⁠
One of the most important things is realising that a meal or a few drinks every now and then isn’t going to mess up your progress or undo all of the work you’ve put in. Enjoying and embracing it will only increase dietary adherence in most cases.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
However, the issue comes when you press the “fuck it” button. When you think that one untracked meal has ruined your day, weekend or week. So you keep going because “you’ve ruined it so you may as well enjoy it”⁠⁠
⁠⁠
And over the next few days you notice your weight and measurements increasing, and your suspicion is confirmed - that meal out on Friday messed you up.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
But it wasn’t that one meal. More often than not, you’re probably still within your weekly calorie goal, especially if you’re at maintenance or above.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Even when you’re in a deficit, what really matters is your weekly average. So even if you were a bit higher on one day, chances are it’ll even out.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
It takes a lot of extra calories to push you out of a weekly deficit and into a surplus.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Will one doughnut do it? Nah.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Will one main course do it? Nah.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Will letting an enjoyable meal turn into a binge because you feel guilty ruin your progress? Yeah maybe. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Feeling guilty and promising you’ll start again on Monday can make a meal turn into a main course with a side of chips, a milkshake, a bottle of wine, a dessert and a share size bag of sweets, followed by a takeaway the next day.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Don’t get stuck into an all or nothing attitude. Think of your effort and adherence like a thermostat. Dial it up high when you can, and at times if you need to turn it down a little bit, then do. But don’t turn it off completely either.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Learn how to enjoy the meals and foods you love. Because 9 times outta 10, it’s not the food that’s stalking your progress, it’s the feelings of guilt that lead to a fuck it attitude and a binge that is.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Self compassion and balance are key 🔑 ⁠⁠

THE HABIT OF COUNTING DOWN

This is something which has positives and negatives. I love having things to look forward to and prepare for like holidays, Christmas, restaurants etc. I always look forward to these way before and plan/imagine it to a tee in my head

This is beneficial because it gives me something to look forward too, however I find I have created the perfect situation in my head and spent so long thinking about it that when it comes to the actual day, it is disappointing

I think this is self sabotaging as I set myself up for failure, for example if I’ve imagined I was going to have the nicest meal ever and then I don’t, I think that it was not as good as it was supposed to be but in fact it was actually what was always going to happen I just imagined my own scenario

I always try to be positive so I usually imagine things to turn out so well but this isn’t always the case

I would love to know your opinions on this topic and if anyone feels the same

🍩🥃I SLACKED ON MY ADHERENCE TO SAY THE LEAST 📖📒

There was a time when it would be hard for me to admit that, as humans we typically don’t like receiving the blame and being held accountable for our actions...

But if you’re not to blame.... who can fix it and make progress...?

That’s why PERSONAL ACCOUNTABILITY is so crucial for success no matter what your goals are 

This is my last check in in Canada vs most recent check in here in Playa Del Carmen, Quintana Roo, Mexico

Yeah I’ll admit it, I didn’t follow my program the best for a little and probably slowed down my progress a bit...

But being able to say that is what makes the difference between being successful and being unsuccessful most of the time 

What I do is take my mistakes/failures/losses/whatever you want to call them - and I’m brutally honest with myself about what I could have done to Ave a better outcome 

What I found is that that allows me to be responsible for my success, and adjust course and try again 

After all anyone at all who is successful will tell you that there were a lot of mistakes and failures before that success right?

So why would we be any different?

Why take setbacks so personally?

Murphy’s law states that anything that can go wrong will go wrong - so make a note of that and remember it when things do go wrong - because they will - and eventually you’ll be able to laugh when stuff happens because it’s all part of the process 🤙🏼🏝☃️

Syn Free Tartar Sauce

Another fridge staple in our house. Goes with seafood but also with plenty of other dishes in place of mayo. Tastes great in sandwiches.

I make a whole bottle of tartar sauce using lighter than light mayo, gherkins, capers, dill, lemon juice and the liquid from the gherkin jar. Just chop a mix together by shaking the bottle.  The whole bottle comes to 5 syns and the amount I usually use would be less than a quarter of a Syn hence I’ve classed it as Syn free 😊

It’s quite runny so I serve in a little bowl or you could add more mayo/less liquid but remember to adjust

Hey hiiiiii it's me. 

I wanted to share with you the story of the moment I knew fitness was what I wanted to do.

So I'm training at my local PureGym one night with a friend, we'd never trained together before but we bonded over our shared enthusiasm and passion for fitness so we decided hey why not do a session together. 
Well anyways this is the night that changed my liiife (not even being dramatic swears).
From the moment we got into the gym it was different. I mean I'd been to that gym 100s of times prior but it just felt different like I hadnt properly seen it before. 
We got on leg press and he said you can definitely do this weight *inserts peg to massive hefty weight I'd never done before* and I was like woah nooo I canny. He said *proper serious like* hol. You can - and I did???? I was like wait whaaatt 🤯 the entire session I was MAXED out anyways lifting weights I would never have dared to attempt before but when I say I was THRIVING. Feeling strength I didn't even know I had?? It was in-cred-ible. I was totally impressing myself because I didn't realise my own capability. 

And that's when it hit me. If it wasn't for my friend at that moment believing in me more than I did, I never would've realised how much I could do. That feeling is what I want to give to others. I want to help and inspire those to find the strength they can't see in themselves. Because sometimes all we need is that little extra push from someone who recognises the things you can't see in yourself. 

Anyways. I'll let you go but yeah that's basically it. If you've managed to read the whole thing then you deserve an actual medal. You're the real ones 🖤🖤🖤

A DAY OF PBs 🥳🥳

Today was glute day and I woke up this morning ready to smash a PB. I was only going for one on hip thrusts today but in the end I got a sumo deadlift PB as well 🥳.

I achieved my May goal of reaching 100kg hip thrust. Was slowly working my way up to get 100kg for 6 but pushed myself and managed to squeeze out a couple more and ended up getting 100kg for 8! My glutes were burning by the end 🥵.

Then after Tuesday’s fail at deadlifts I wasn’t backing myself to do well but ended up lifting 55kg for 10 which is also a PB!! 

Finished off the glute workout with:
✨ Sumo squats- 20kg
✨ Curtsy lunges- 15kg. I can deffo go heavier but they just scare me. Just cannot get my balance right 🙃
✨ Goblet squats- 12kg
✨ Cable pull throughs (didn’t film)

I’m already feeling sore so tomorrow is going to be a struggle I’m sure 🥵.

Hope you all have a fab weekend ❤️

182.5kg / 402lb squat

So I've now passed the 400 pound mark on squats. Consistently/continuously I've probably been squatting heavy for about 10-11 months, with a fair bit of disruption going on in between... climbing mountains and not being able to squat heavy at all for 9 months of the last year with the gym closures. 

Maybe had a few more kilos there, but I don't want to be getting into a habit of grindy squat maxes and failing heavy squats.

Decent milestone to pass anyway 🏋️

A lifting belt is a piece of equipment designed to increase “intra-abdominal pressure”. 
 
Intra- meaning inside
Abdominal- meaning your abdomen
And pressure...is pressure.

So we are increasing the pressure inside our abdomen. 
This increased intra-abdominal pressure makes our trunk more rigid, allowing for more stability when we lift, in turn resulting in a small increase in performance when it comes to resistance training. 

On top of that, a lifting belt can sometimes decrease someone’s levels of pain while lifting especially with low back pain.

Do you always feel hungry but not sure why or how to make the feeling go away without just eating! 

Here is my top 5 tips 
- Drink more water, it has the potential to reduce your appetite when you consume your meals. Feelings of thirst can be mistaken for hunger.
- Eat more protein, as it has hunger reducing properties that will help you automatically consume less calories throughout the day.
- Nutritious meals, having meals with a healthy balance of Macros helps you stay fuller for longer. Processed foods can actually make your feel hungry after eating them
- Get enough sleep, studies have shown too little sleep can increase hunger by 24%
- Are you actually eating enough? Having too little calories will obviously make you hungry. Being on a calorie deficit means getting the balance right

caption:
The secret to bigger arms💪🏻

Real talk, who doesn't want bigger arms?😅

The answer is simple, we all do. Having muscular arms demands respect, it's a very masculine look that we all desire.

A big, strong upper body has always been the goal for any fitness enthusiast. 

From a wide chest to a pair of round shoulders, these muscles make the physique and having abs is definitely a plus..

But how often are we walking around with our shirts off?🤷🏼‍♂️

When you're building your body, you need to be practical, and strength comes from the arms. So let's dive into the basics of building bigger arms.

The solution? Moving away from the basics and focusing on a few key advanced concepts, you can add slabs of muscle to your arms and start splitting your sleeves in no time.

✅Technique 1: Progressive overload

With progressive overload, you’ll continually lift more to make your muscles work harder than they’re accustomed to. 

This excess demand will help you to make gains in muscle size, strength and endurance.

Here are three ways you can progressively overload your muscles.

1. Increase resistance – Add more weight

2. Increase sets – add a couple more sets to each exercise

3. Increase reps- mix up your volume with higher and lower rep schemes. 

✅Technique 2: Time under tension (TUT)

Time under tension simply refers to how long a specific muscle group is under strain during a set. 

You can probably do 10 reps of barbell bicep curls in about 15-20 seconds. 

But simply by doing them more slowly, you can increase that time under tension to 35-40 seconds. 

This forces your biceps to work 15-20 seconds longer allowing the muscle fibers to grow.

By combining progresive overload and tempo training with a sound bicep and tricep program, your muscles will have no choice but to grow. 🔥

I CAN’T BE BOTHERED TO GO TO THE GYM, PLEASE HELP!

One of the most common questions I get is, how can I stay motivated?

Motivation can only get you so far, sometimes you might wake up and feel super pumped and ready to smash your session! 💪🏻 However, the other time you might wake up and not feel super pumped. 😩 This is totally normal, everyone can’t be super motivated all the time!

However, what if there was something else that could keep you going? 🤔

DISCIPLINE💪🏻

Discipline is going to get you to be able to tick off your boxes and get everything done which needs to be done! ✅

HOW DO I FIND DISCIPLINE???
 
You’ve got to dig deep! You’ve got to ask yourself: 

Do I really want this?
Do I really need this?
Am I ready to change?

Use these answers to push through the lack of motivation! If you want it, you’ve got to work for it! 🙌🏻

first week back at the gymmm 🥳🤸🏾‍♀️

now atm im still only going for leg day and doing upper body at home. i must say it has been nice being back, but it’s crazy to think how my priorities has shifted since working out from home.

I never used to focus on my form the way I do. I also never prioritised getting in cardio because i didn’t feel I needed it for my “goals” and would only incorporate it into my workouts when cutting.

Now, while I will not sit here and pretend I don’t still have aesthetic body goals, because I do, i have  come to understand the importance of prioritizing how i feel over how I look. And tbh, despite gyming consistently for some time now, i still didn’t feel “fit” and I wanted to change that.

since working out from home, i focused mainly on improving my form and my cardiovascular fitness, as I felt I had neglected this prior.

Not only has this been super enjoyable but I have seen such an improvement in the quality of my workouts. Not to say they’re the best, as I am aware that there is soo much room for improvement. 

However, I am grateful for how much I’ve learned while working out from home and excited to use the new knowledge make some gains 😌🥰

The last lockdown was a bit rough on my health both mentally and physically, and seen as it’s mental health week I thought It’d only be fitting to share some of my recent experiences with my own mental health. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I’ve always struggled with anxiety and low levels of depression at times but this last lockdown hit me HARD... I found myself so weak, I even got quite sick from not eating well, not training, not drinking...not doing anything really. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I realised I was slipping and my health was getting worse when I got sick. I couldn’t get my mind off of my fitness and how I just needed the gym back and all of this would stop! Ive used the gym and lifting weights as a form of therapy for myself for a round about year or so now, when I’m training (and not in a pandemic) I’m in the best place mentally than I’ve been for a long long time. 
Training has taught me discipline, how to look after my health, to love myself, to be proud of what my body can do and so much more. It’s given me a whole new outlook on life and this is still only the beginning for me in reality! 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
It’s been a week and a half of being back in the gym and already I’m feeling so much better! My physical and mental health is coming back just as fast as I knew it would. I’m also finding so many other ways to keep my mental health up, so that I’m not relying on the gym to be open...2021 and all...who knows if we will go into another lockdown 🤷🏼‍♀️😂 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

We need to stop praising weight loss !
.
Stop with the comments, “wow you look so skinny!”, “you look so thin!” etc., while most people think being called skinny is a compliment it really can be detrimental to someone’s mental health. When I was going through my eating disorder and got these comments it only fueled me more to starve myself longer. When I get these comments now (which I do almost everyday 🙄) while I’m recovering from an eating disorder it makes me feel not good enough, like I’m not doing enough in my recovery.
.
Weight Loss does NOT = Healthy
Someone could be severely depressed and losing weight or suffering from an eating disorder and you’re praising their unhealthy weight loss. 
.
So let’s start praising muscle growth, hitting new PRs, going to the gym on a consistent basis, hitting 10k steps a day and eating without guilt 🧁
.
Also, while we’re at it, stop asking me how much I weigh okay :))))))
.
.

🌟Beginner Friendly, Full Body Workout🌟

🙏You guys need to SAVE this workout, for your next gym day🙏

Who just has those days where they want to smash a workout but they don't know what they want to do? 

That's when I LOVE a full body day! 

I thought, after the incredible feedback I had after I uploaded my upper body beginner workout, I would put together a full body one too💪

As you can see on the videos, I use one small area of the free weights section in the gym. I use dumbbells, a weighted plate and a light barbell, that's all you need! 

If you're nervous / anxious about going in the free weight section, unsure what to do or what equipment to use, GET THIS WORKOUT SAVED AND TRY IT OUT! 

Don't forget to go light on these weights, especially if you're new to weight training. To complete 3 sets of 12 reps, you really don't want to be going too heavy to finish the circuits. 

Pointers:

🏋️‍♀️ Squeeze your Glutes for at least 1 second at the top of the Glute Bridge. 
🏋️‍♀️Go extra light on the front / lat raises, your shoulders will burn with little weight, trust me. 
🏋️‍♀️On the BB RDLs, keep your back straight and push your hips back. Keep going until you feel your hamstrings stretch and then return to the start position. Everyone has different flexibility with these so don't compare yourself to anyone else. Once you feel the stretch, that's enough🙌

Receiving feedback from those who try my workouts really does make my whole week, so if you do try this one, please just drop me a message and let me know what you thought🙏

RUN THROUGH:

🌟Plate Squat into Steering Wheels
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Barbell RDL into Upright Row
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Dumbbell Lateral to Front Raises
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Barbell Glute Bridges
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Dumbbell Bent Over Rows
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Dumbbell Hammer Curl into Shoulder Press
- 3 sets of 12 reps
🌟Dumbbell Reverse Lunges
- 3 sets of 12 reps (each leg)

(HOPELIJK😜) Gaan de sportscholen over een paar dagen weer open en zijn we af van de thuis workouts! 🥳 Ik denk dat het voor iedereen weer even wennen zal zijn en daarom heb ik een paar tips voor jullie maar ook voor mezelf 🤣 zodat jij lekker kan gaan knallen! Zonder dat je je misschien ongemakkelijk of onzeker gaat voelen.🙃

💛 Draag iets waar jij je mooi en comfortabel in voelt! 

💛 Knal jouw favoriete workout playlist aan.🎵

💛 Plan je workout en schrijf het uit. Een goede voorbereiding is het halve werk.🙃

💛 Vraag om hulp. Iedereen heeft wel eens gehad dat hij/zij geen idee had hoe een bepaald apparaat werkt. Don’t be afraid en vraag het, er zijn genoeg lieve mensen die jou willen helpen!

💛 Ga niet meteen all in en  200% Bouw het rustig op, eet voldoende, slaap voldoende en pak je rust!

Vergeet niet, iedereen is “onderaan” begonnen toen hij/zij net binnenkwam in de sportschool! You’re not the only one💕 Can’t wait tot we weer mogen!

WHAT TO KEEP IN MIND WHEN TRYING TO GET ABS:
I get a load of people come and ask me for abs workouts telling me all they want is to get abs. The reality is, the only way you can get abs is by losing fat by eating in a calorie deficit. Especially for those of you trying to bulk up, getting abs (and being in a calorie deficit) is just going to make it harder to gain muscle. Training abs everyday will not get you abs, you have to be at a low enough body fat to see them. If you are trying to gain muscle you are far better off lean bulking then cutting back any fat you have gained and any you had to start with. Dropping fat before you start going to the gym will not get you a ripped physique.

Obviously if you have a lot of fat to begin with you can lose fat and gain muscle (body recomposition), eating in a calorie deficit where your body will burn the fat to make up the excess calories to build however for the majority this is going to be inefficient and make it harder for you to reach your goals.

You have to also remember that as with the rest of ‘bodybuilding’ or with any sport a lot of it is down to genetics, some people will have far better/or worse insertions and metabolisms which will make it easier or harder to get abs respectively.

There is no ‘quick fix’ to getting abs so bear that in mind when working towards whatever your goals are, whether you bulk or cut doing either excessively will not be beneficial and will leave you worse off than where you are now. 

Keep working hard and you will get there.

Stay strong, and get Huuuge 💪🏼💪🏼

caption:
But you BURN SO MANY CALORIES CLAY! 

“You burn more fat”

“You tone up faster”

Actually quite the opposite 

Do you burn more calories in that short time period (compared to strength training)? 

100%.

But wouldn’t you rather burn more calories in the other 23.5 hours in a day instead?

Here’s why HIIT workouts aren’t as effective as you think⬇️

1) They suck at building muscle 

When it comes to being more “toned” or more “muscular” you need to be working out in a way that actually promotes 💪 

HIIT uses little to no resistance and is not applying enough muscle damage directly to the muscles we want to grow (like our 🍑).

2) You RELY on that workout to burn calories 

Yes, you will burn some calories in a short amount of time. This will make up about 10% of your TOTAL calorie burn for the day.

While strength training helps you burn more calories for the other 90% of the day.

Work smarter not harder 😎

3) HIIT workouts don’t really apply progressive overload (the main component to get stronger). 

So basically your just burning calories, which has its place in any workout routine, but should not be the sole focus and be used as a SUPPLEMENT towards your goals😤

4) Only a small population can actually do them effectively.

Burpees, push ups, mountain climbers, are all movements that are taxing on our bodies 

And for someone who’s already overweight & self conscious... do you really think they will do these movements consistently? 

Compared to strength training where ANYONE can start where they’re at and progress from there😁

Do you get my point?

.
Deadlift 185x5 RPE 6.5 — I’m actually really starting to enjoy deadlifts which says A LOT considering I absolutely dreaded doing these when I first started 😹 I am forever underestimating my physical ability and strength and deadlifts have really pushed me to tap into my true strength while also exercising my mind a little bit. If you could hear the conversations going on in my head while I do these... lol. Deadlifts felt smooth like butter this week :-) 
.
.
Assisted pull-ups — it had been a while since I’d done these but I was pretty excited about how good they felt! When I did these last summer I required ~100lbs of assistance for about the same amount of reps that I only needed 65.5-72lbs for yesterday! Also had to peep the back gains 😻 loving how my back is filling out. I don’t have any of my pull-ups from last summer filmed so the next best thing was my lat pull downs from Dec 2020 (slide 3) and Oct 2020 (slide 4).

caption:
What brings you absolute joy?
.
In case you hadn't noticed, for me, it's bright colourful gymwear, the ability and opportunity to train hard and FOOOD!
.
I feel that exercise and eating should bring you joy. Maybe not EVERY SINGLE DAY but for a good 90% of your week it's important to enjoy the journey and the process. 
.
Have a training plan and include exercises that are both going to help you reach your goals AND you those you enjoy doing. 
.
When it comes to nutrition not all plans work for all. Counting calories, macros, portions sizes, fasting, intermittent fasting, intuative eating --- each one has it's pro's and con's so make sure you choose the right one for you again to help you with goals AND ensure you aren't miserable.
.
I've found my happy balance, loving training, great nutrition plan and a big part of that comes from my coach but also knowing what works for me, what makes me happy and what I want out of my training and nutrition.
.
In a nutshell you do you. Don't just follow what your friend is doing, take time to look at where you want to be and what you're willing to sacrifice. 
.
If you need any help or advice drop me a message 💜
.

Monke

When I first created this account, I was SO worried about what other people would think. Although I was comfortable in myself & within the gym, I was worried that people would think I was a try hard/wonder who I thought I was for posting about my gym progress 😂 

If you know me you’ll know I hate being the centre of attention, so me making a page literally dedicated to my fitness was a big deal😂 I took a step out my comfort zone making this account, because I wanted to make other people feel more comfortable. 

I know first hand (even still now!) how uncomfortable women can feel in the gym. We’re stared at, followed around, inappropriate questions asked (someone asked me how much I weighed 🙃). Why is it STILL that some people see women as being aliens in the gym?😂 

My “audience” (hate that word lol) is primarily women aged around 18-24, so my sort of age, and the age I’d imagine it’s most common to feel uncomfortable in the gym. Don’t get me wrong, I do not feel 100% comfortable all of the time - but I’ve learned that that’s not a reflection on me, but on other people’s weird behaviour😂 

Soooo, here are the things I do/have done to make myself feel more comfortable in the gym ❤️ 

1️⃣wear an outfit you love/feel good in - honestly think this is so underrated & I know for me anyway it can massively affect my workout 😂😭

2️⃣ make friends!! I know this isn’t easy, and I’ve been lucky in the sense my boyfriend works at my gym, but having friends that I know will keep an eye out for me if someone makes me uncomfortable has been realllly nice 

3️⃣ MUSIC!!!!!! I know we probably all will listen to music whilst training, but having a good playlist that you genuinely enjoy, so you’re not having to skip songs all the time is a game changer lol 

4️⃣ take some time getting used to the exercises you’re doing. idk about anyone else but I used to get so paranoid I’d be doing things wrong and people would laugh, which would prevent me from doing them at all. YouTube is your friend - the amount of times I’ve looked up tutorials of how to do stuff/set things up is a joke hahaha 

5️⃣ remember you have just as much right to be there as anybody else 💘

Little late but, this is only part of my routine. Took it easy today, listened to my body and not go to heavy. Instead, doing TUT (Time Under Tension) while doing the Leg Extension, Press, and Seated Calf Raises.

WORKOUT:

• Sumo Deadlift: 4X12 (light weight)

Some of my staple back/pull day exercises! 

It’s been a pretty tough few weeks. I lost my grandfather to COVID. Wrote my last finals ever & working on graduation with tons of to-do’s piling up—and I didn’t want to go to the gym at all

I can go for as many walks, runs, do homeworkouts all I want, but the gym is my “me time”. My focus is different than anywhere else I can do the exact same exercises. It’s where I clear my head, release my stress & don’t think about anything but pushing the weight 

Exercising is more than just the aesthetic, or physical component. I do it for my mental health more than anything. 

Here was some of yesterday’s workout & don’t forget to engage your core!! I did moderate weight and higher reps for this workout

1️⃣ Bent over rows 3x12 

2️⃣ Wide grip lat pull downs 4x10 

3️⃣ Back extensions (pyramid up with progressively heavier weight, 3x8-10 with hardest weight & pyramid back down)

4️⃣ Dumbbell bicep curls- 3 rep groups per arm! Love these 3x9. Slow & controlled and aim for a tricep flex at the end of the movement to ensure full rom

*Some exercises not recorded: close grip lat pulldown, seated single arm row, cable straight arm pulldown & cable bicep curls

Is the gym your “happy place”?

IT'S FRIDAYYY!! But more importantly ITS SUMMER!! A quote for me by me- “No one else did it but you” - I DID IT! This year has been one of the most brutal years academically and mentally. With Covid, and I’m a public health major on the pre-med track, my classes have been insane. All of the last nights in the library staying up till 12 am to wake up the next day and study more for organic chemistry are finally over! This is my first real break since Sept of 2019... last summer, I took 5 summer courses to get ahead. I need this break, time to focus on me, focus on my health, body, mind, and soul!! This summer will be all about self-growth, self-acceptance, and self-love! with getting strong asf of course! What are your summer goals? Comin attcha with a killer glute-focused leg day!! Like; Save; Share with your friends! Here are the deets ✨
***
🦋Warm-up: Glute activation: Not shown
10 x banded walks each leg
10 x banded kickbacks
10 x banded fire hydrants
20 x glute bridges 
***
🦋 4 x 12- Banded Hip Thrusts 
🦋 3 x 25- Dumbbell Frog Pump
🦋 3 x 20- Banded Clams Each Side
🦋 3 x 20- Banded Glute Bride With Abduction 
🦋 3 x 20- Banded Side Crab Walks 
🦋 3 x 30- Hip Abduction
***
🦋 Cool Down- 2 sets of Glute Burnout Exercises
***
OH BABBY!! This left my abductors on fire for days!! Always have to start a glute day off with Hip Thrusts!! If you’ve noticed a lot of my workouts are similar, it’s because I stick to the same compound movements and progressively overload... that’s key to getting stronger and building muscle!! Give this workout a go and build those glutes!! Here’s to the weekend! And all my college friends we freakin did it! Always remember it’s a New Day- New Goals- New Affirmations 🤍🦋✨

Para ser honesto nunca he tenido miedo a perder tamaño, ni estar "desinflado", es un proceso, a veces te toca estar grande, a veces te toca estar pequeño, por ello lo ideal es tener esa fortaleza mental, o esa gestión emocional, de que no estarás de una determinada forma todo el tiempo (y siendo sinceros, a menos que te dediques a esto, tampoco la necesitas)

Los que estamos en el medio del fitness, normalmente no vivimos de nuestros físicos, si no de nuestras cabezas. Y claro, entre más sepas, mejor desarrollo puedes tener, más variables puedes considerar, y menos agravantes puedes tener.

Puedes sacar el máximo beneficio, con el mínimo utilizable.

El camino nunca es sencillo, pero vale la pena recorrerlo. Al menos para no pensar el resto de tu vida con un "Y si hubiera...." atravesado en la garganta.

If you are past the beginner’s stage and want to gain muscle, one of the best body part splits you can use to accomplish this is the push/pull/legs split routine.⁣
-
The essence of push/pull(legs is that you split your body into three body parts, where each body part is trained on its own separate day. On your push day you train chest, shoulders and triceps. In the pull workout you train the back and biceps. Lastly, on the leg day you train your quads, hamstring and calfs. Some people also train abdominals on leg day. ⁣
-
With push/pull/legs you train all related muscle groups together. This means that you get the maximum overlap of movements within the same workout, and the muscle groups being trained get an overall benefit from this overlap.⁣
-
For example when you train chest with say bench press, you are also hitting your anterior deltoids and triceps hard. And when you train shoulders you are again involving your triceps. So it makes sense to work these all together in the same workout for maximum synergy and effectiveness.⁣
-
Similarly when you train your back your biceps are heavily involved, so it again makes sense to train these immediately afterwards so that they can derive the maximum benefit from the additional stimulation.⁣

Here’s how you want to run it👇🏻👇🏻

✅ A1 - Arm Supported DB External Rotation - 3 x 8-10, 3010, 30s

✅ A2 - Single Arm Bent Over Lateral Raise - 3 x 8-10, 3010, 30s

✅ B1 - V Bar Dip - 10,8,6,6,8,10, 3010, 90s

✅ B2 - Standing Thick Bar Reverse Curl - 10,8,6,6,8,10, 3010, 90s

✅ C1 - Single Arm DB lateral Raise - 2-3 x 8-10, 3010, 10s

✅ C2 - Single Arm DB L-Lateral Raise - 2-3 x 12-15, 2010, 60s

This workout will help shoulder structural balance from left to right *Start with your weaker side on the single arm work…..strong side does same reps as weaker side 😉

For the pyramid👇🏻

Aim to hit a max set of 6 on your 4th set🔥

From there, back off on the load each set & hit the reps laid out and watch your arms fill by the set 😉

Set 1 start with 1-2 reps in reserve & add load each set as the reps go down

Example - 
1 - 50 x 10
2 - 52.5 x 8
3 - 55 x 6
4 - 57.5 x 6
5 - 55 x 8
6 - 52.5 x 10

Set 4-6 should be your big working sets…..enjoy them 😜

If you need any exercise variations than the ones above or have any questions, just drop a in the comments👇🏻👇🏻👇🏻

This is your reminder to wear whatever you feel comfortable wearing in the gym. When I say comfortable I mean something that means: 
🥵 you don’t get uncomfortably hot 
🥶you don’t freeze between sets 
🤩you feel confident 
😌you feel secure 

I often change my outfit a million times before going to the gym bc I worry about people staring or that someone might see me in an unflattering angle. I’m not going to keep my jumper on and pass out from overheating for the benefit of someone else (although in a gym full of men sometimes it feels like the best option) 

You do you boo, don’t worry about anyone else or their opinions because they really aren’t important

- Use a hook grip to incorporate the biceps less and make it more back focussed!

Achieving a difficult task trains your brain to push past the discomfort, continue when things get hard, and follow through with your intentions. 

Purposefully challenging yourself establishes discipline, and improves your ability to take control of your mind. 

I try remind myself that “mind over matter” is very relevant in sports/ exercise but also in all aspects of life. I believe that training yourself to continue, especially when you don’t want to, or feel like you can’t, is where growth comes from. 

I have so much to chase after, but I know that as long as I keep pushing myself out of my comfort zone and seeking new challenges I will have continuous growth in all areas of my life. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
